# Team Member Skills

Group discussion has revealed that all team members are proficient in the Python programming language and have some experience with web-based languages (i.e. HTML, CSS, JS). However, the team needs to gain experience constructing GUIs using frameworks. One team member has some knowledge of machine vision theory and has a working knowledge of the Python library OpenCV.

# Required Resources

The client requires a desktop GUI application that can select an image file on their machine, identify visual features, perform analysis, and then represent the results as plots in the GUI. As per *Figure 1*, this will be realised using software with two main components: the GUI and the image data extraction process. The software need not be dockerized as dependencies are minimal (i.e. just a Python environment with several libraries) and, as per discussion with the client, it is not critical that this application be platform independent. 

The Python Library OpenCV will be used to construct the image data extraction component, as it is both an industry standard and what team members have experience with.

The choice of framework for the GUI component initially needed to be clarified. This decision, however, was guided by six main constraints:  
			

1. It should have a simple, user-friendly experience.  
2. It should be in a shared coding language.  
3. It should interact comfortably with OpenCV and plotting libraries like Matplotlib.  
4. Its licence should be compatible with the licence applied to the software.   
5. It should allow the software to be quickly packaged into an installer for delivery.

We evaluated several GUI frameworks before PyQt was selected. See *Table 1* for more detail.

### GUI Framework Testing 

A simple, ‘hello world’ application was created using PyQt to test whether OpenCV and Matplotlib could be successfully integrated. The integration was successful, with only minimal middleware required.

		![][image1]  
*Figure 1: A simple software architecture diagram of the Sediment Colour Application running on a user’s machine.*

***Table 1: GUI frameworks***  

| Tool | Overview | Potential Issues |
| ----- | :---- | :---- |
| *PyQt* | A complete Python GUI framework. Has considerable documentation. | Has a slightly steeper learning curve than alternatives, which may slow down development |
| *Electron* | A framework that runs web dev code on a Chromium engine. Has strong cross-platform portability.  | Takes up slightly more space on a user’s machine than alternatives.  |
| *PySimpleGUI*  | Easy to learn and use. Has cross-platform compatibility. | Limited customisation options compared to more advanced frameworks |
| *GuiZero* | Designed to allow new learners to quickly and easily create GUIs for their programs | Not an industry-standard framework. |
